<DocPageMeta Title="Template parameters"
             Section="Get Started"
             Order="30"
             Status="DocPageStatus.Draft"
             Description="Every parameter the dotnet new shift template accepts, what it controls, and when to change it."
             Keywords="template,parameters,dotnet new shift,includeSampleApp,shiftIdentityHostingType,addFunctions,addTest,external identity" />

<DocSection Title="Required parameters">
    <p>
        Two parameters must be passed every time you run <code>dotnet new shift</code>.
        The CLI will refuse to scaffold without them.
    </p>

    <h3><code>--includeSampleApp</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> boolean &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>true</code></p>
    <p>
        Controls whether the generated project ships with the <b>StockPlusPlus</b>
        sample app — a working inventory system covering products, brands, categories,
        invoices, file uploads, lookups, and a Blazor admin UI. The sample exists so
        you have something runnable from the very first build instead of an empty
        skeleton.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>true</code> — generate the full sample, including controllers, repositories, DTOs, entities, AutoMapper profiles, mappers, action trees, and Blazor pages. <b>Recommended for your first project.</b></li>
        <li><code>false</code> — generate a clean skeleton with only the framework wiring (Program.cs, DbContext, identity setup) and no business code. Pick this when you already understand the framework and want a blank canvas.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3><code>--shiftIdentityHostingType</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> choice &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>Internal</code> &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Values:</b> <code>Internal</code> | <code>External</code></p>
    <p>Controls how ShiftIdentity (the user/role/permission backend) is hosted:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>Internal</code> — ShiftIdentity runs <b>inside</b> the same API process as your app. Identity tables live in the same database, identity endpoints (<code>/IdentityPublicUser</code>, the dashboard, etc.) are exposed by your API, and there's nothing else to deploy. <b>This is the right choice for almost every new project.</b></li>
        <li><code>External</code> — your app does <b>not</b> host identity. It expects a separate ShiftIdentity instance to authenticate against. Pick this only when you already run a central ShiftIdentity that multiple downstream apps share. You'll also need to set <code>--externalShiftIdentityApi</code> and <code>--externalShiftIdentityFrontEnd</code> below.</li>
    </ul>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Tip">
        If you're not sure, choose <code>Internal</code>. You can always migrate to
        an external setup later — but starting with <code>Internal</code> means
        fewer moving parts to deploy and debug while you're learning the framework.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Optional parameters">
    <h3><code>--addFunctions</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> boolean &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>false</code></p>
    <p>
        Adds an Azure Functions project (<code>YourApp.Functions</code>) alongside
        the API. Use this when your project needs scheduled jobs (timer triggers),
        queue/blob handlers, or background processing that lives outside the API
        request lifecycle. The Functions project comes pre-wired with TypeAuth
        permissions and Shift Framework conventions.
    </p>
    <p>
        Skip this if you're not sure you need it. It's easy enough to add a
        Functions project later by hand.
    </p>

    <h3><code>--addTest</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> boolean &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>false</code></p>
    <p>
        Adds an xUnit integration test project (<code>YourApp.Test</code>) that
        spins up a real in-memory database and exercises your repositories and
        controllers end-to-end. Useful for projects that take testing seriously
        from day one.
    </p>

    <h3><code>--externalShiftIdentityApi</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> string &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>""</code> (empty)</p>
    <p>
        <b>Only used when <code>--shiftIdentityHostingType External</code>.</b>
        Base URL of your external ShiftIdentity API, for example
        <code>https://identity.example.com</code>. Gets baked into the generated
        <code>appsettings.json</code> as the <code>ShiftIdentityApi</code> value.
    </p>

    <h3><code>--externalShiftIdentityFrontEnd</code></h3>
    <p><b>Type:</b> string &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Default:</b> <code>""</code> (empty)</p>
    <p>
        <b>Only used when <code>--shiftIdentityHostingType External</code>.</b>
        Base URL of the external ShiftIdentity frontend (the dashboard/login UI).
        Often the same host as the API. Gets baked into the generated
        <code>appsettings.json</code> as the <code>ShiftIdentityFrontEnd</code> value.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Auto-generated values you don't pass">
    <p>
        A few values are computed by the template engine itself when it scaffolds
        your project. You don't need to set these, but it's worth knowing they
        exist so you understand what's in your generated files.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><b>User secret IDs</b> — fresh GUIDs for the API and Functions projects, used by the .NET user-secrets store so each developer's local secrets stay scoped to their project.</li>
        <li><b>ASP.NET Core dev port</b> — a random free port in the 5000–5300 range, baked into <code>launchSettings.json</code> so two Shift projects on the same machine don't fight for port 5069.</li>
        <li><b>Azure Functions dev port</b> — a random free port in the 7000–7300 range, used the same way for the optional Functions project.</li>
        <li><b>Project GUIDs</b> — every project (API, Data, Shared, Web) gets a fresh <code>ProjectGuid</code> so two scaffolded solutions don't collide if you ever combine them in a parent solution.</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Common combinations">
    <h3>First-time learner (recommended)</h3>
    <p>Get a fully working sample with internal identity, no extras:</p>
    <DocSnippet Name="ScaffoldFirstProject" Language="bash" />

    <h3>Production-ready starting point with tests and background jobs</h3>
    <p>The same as above, plus the test project and Functions project:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">dotnet new shift -n MyApp \
    --includeSampleApp true \
    --shiftIdentityHostingType Internal \
    --addFunctions true \
    --addTest true</code></pre>

    <h3>Empty skeleton, no sample, external identity</h3>
    <p>For when you already understand the framework and have a central identity service:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">dotnet new shift -n MyApp \
    --includeSampleApp false \
    --shiftIdentityHostingType External \
    --externalShiftIdentityApi https://identity.example.com \
    --externalShiftIdentityFrontEnd https://identity.example.com</code></pre>
</DocSection>

